  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Better Business for Children Turkey</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In Turkey, 720,000 children in the age group of 5 to 17 years are engaged in child labour. Significant of these numbers can be linked to the garment and textile supply chain. The biggest challenge in tackling child labour in this sector in Turkey is the fact that the supply chain is strongly fragmented with many (big) producers outsourcing to smaller factories or homeworkers.Because of the widespread outsourcing and subcontracting this project will first focus on mapping the specific supply chains linked to the participating brands and their risks (project A). This analysis will determine the location(s) of the improvement programme of project B.Project A will result in a clear mapping of the supply chains of minimum one to maximum two suppliers of the participating brands, and a risk assessment indicating the risks in that particular supply chain(s). Based on these results and in agreement and sphere of influence of all participants, the location with the highest risks on the violation of children&#x2019;s rights will be prioritized for action in project B.In project B the partnership will work on the risks determined in project A through, for example, implementing UNICEF&#x2019;s Better Business for Children (BB4C) programme in the selected locations, and if needed for their support, include higher tiers.</narrative>
  </description>
